employs a large and diverse staff, from waiters to cooks to cleaners. The majority are rather forgettable, skilled in the art of fading into the background. In fact, most regular customers would struggle to remember the faces of many of the waitstaff, and wouldn't recognize them on the street. There are exceptions, however. The Midnight Sun's head bartenders are very memorable indeed, and would be recognized anywhere in town by anyone who frequents the bar. The other bartenders are less memorable, and fade into the blur of faceless waitstaff.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Alan is the youngest of the four head bartenders. Born to an extremely poor family, he ended up a street urchin at the ripe old age of four. Growing up, he began an apprenticeship with a master assassin specializing in mixing poisons and toxins. Throughout the apprenticeship, Alan learned that he was rather adept at making poisons specifically tailored to the target. After his master died under suspicious circumstances, Alan set out on his own. Unfortunately, the economy was not kind to startup poisoners, so Alan decided to use his skills for something a little more marketable: bartending. He was able to easily apply what he'd learned to alcohol, and soon built up quite a following among the drinkers and drunkards of Isra. He can be charming when he needs to be, although he tends to enjoy the suffering of others more than he probably should.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Allen is the oldest bartender, having been around a lot longer than the Midnight Sun. Having lived in the area before the city was built, he watched as Isra grew around him and thus knows the city like the back of his hand. He's taken many jobs before finding his place behind the bar, including, but not limited to:MailmanConstruction workerCheese makerChocolate deliverymanFlower gardenerDancerOpera singerFood criticShoe shinerLine cookFishermanButcherBakerCandlestick makerProfessional love letter writerNewspaper columnistTown guardAmong \u00a0others. He even had a short stint as an adventurer, which ended in a tragic incident involving arrows and knees. His friendly demeanor and wide variety of experience has made him the go-to person to ask for advice, and he's usually very happy to give it.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Ellen grew up in a convent, surrounded by habits and wimples. She became a nun at age 19, blending in with all the others and praying and doing other nun things. Her life was the exact same routine every day after that for the next seven years: a neverending stream of prayer and caring for urchins and the downtrodden. There certainly were a lot of urchins running around. \u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0One day, she looked around and realized that nothing had changed for the better part of a decade. Her life was exactly the same, and she had nothing to show for it. Everyone around her was still nuns, she still spent all day teaching urchins, and she still slept in the same lumpy bed each night at the same time. She'd never had any choice in the matter, and had never thought as to whether she wanted this life or not. She hadn't chosen the nun life. The nun life had chosen her. Ellen realized how bored she was with her routine, and so she snuck out of the convent in the middle of the night without leaving so much as a note. Six days later, she was sitting in a tavern when a group of nuns from her old convent walked in. They spotted her immediately and surrounded her, pleading for her to return. She refused, and they tried to grab her and drag her back against her will. After a short and messy fight, Ellen managed to escape, stealing a horse and riding off into the night. For the next four years, she dodged countless attempts by her former sisters to capture her and bring her back to the convent, forcing her to fake her own death in a house fire to escape the nuns. She eventually made her way to Isra, where she found a job as a bartender. Even after her escape, though, she still looked over her shoulder constantly and avoided going into buildings with only one exit route. Her years working with urchins made her very sympathetic and motherly towards small children, and she disapproves of Heartbreak and other harmful drinks.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0Elin is the newest bartender. The daughter of a roadside tavern owner, she grew up around ale and liquor. All her life, she worked for her parents as a waitress, serving drinks and taking orders. It all went well until a new main road was built, allowing for an easier way to travel through the mountains. The stream of thirsty travelers, which had once seemed endless, suddenly slowed to a trickle. The lack of business caused Elin to move out to the city in search of better wages to help support her parents. Once in Isra, Elin soon acquired a job as a bartender. No longer under the watchful eye of her parents, she started flirting more and more with her customers, earning her more tips than she'd ever imagined. In fact, she found that it was easier and more profitable to spend time chatting with the customers than actually serve drinks, much to the annoyance of her co-workers. Her habit of talking to customers for long periods of time, combined with the fact that she grew up in a fairly small tavern and was still unused to the big-city crowds, caused her co-workers to think of her as lazy and/or easy. Still, she makes more than the other bartenders, and sends much of it back to her parents.", "link_list": [], "image_list": ["http://dustin.wdfiles.com/local--files/reardon-cormaeril/reardon.jpg", "https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/236x/05/04/78/050478efe0c1b76e9f0f5e3ad35709be.jpg", "http://i.imgur.com/nXT9Wuv.png?1", "https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/236x/18/10/e0/1810e0bdf0d44ed37e74adfb623db657.jpg"], "html": "<div style=\"text-align:center;\"><font size=\"5\">The Four Bartenders</font><br><div style=\"text-align:left;\"><span>\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0</span>The Midnight Sun employs a large a